Bayesian model of regularization

Vanessa Ferdinand

7/3/2020

Draft 1 - document still in progress

Overview

This document explains the beta-binomial Bayesian model used in Reali & Griffiths (2008).

Ill explain their model using examples from the problem domain of flipping a coin and trying to infer the bias on the coin from the outcome of the flips you observe.

The model

Prior

The prior distribution is a beta distribution.

\(Beta(\alpha,\beta) = \frac{\Gamma(\alpha+\beta)}{\Gamma(\alpha)\Gamma(\beta)} \theta^{\alpha-1}(1-\theta)^{\beta-1}\)

This is a distribution over your beliefs in what the bias of the coin could be, before you see any data.

\(\theta =\) each hypothesis, or bias that the coin could have.
\(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) control the shape of the prior.

Note: Reali & Griffiths (2008) restrict their model to a symmetrical prior, meaning \(\alpha=\beta\), and use a single parameter with the notation \(\frac{a}{2}\), as in \(Beta(\frac{a}{2},\frac{a}{2})\). Im going to stick to \(Beta(\alpha,\beta)\) in this document so you can explore asymmetrical priors too. But if you want to replicate RG, just use \(\alpha=\beta\).

Examples:
When \(\alpha=\beta=1\), the prior is uniform. Meaning the learner has equal belief in all possible values of \(\theta\) before they see any data.
When \(\alpha=\beta<1\), the learner expects \(\theta\) to be regular (i.e.peaked at \(\theta=0\) and \(\theta=1\)).
When \(\alpha=\beta>1\), the learner expects \(\theta\) to be variable (i.e.peaked at \(\theta=0.5\))
When \(\alpha=5\) and \(\beta=2\), the learner expects \(\theta=0.8\) and biases around that to be most likely.

Plot a beta distribution. Change the parameters alpha and beta below:

alpha <- 5
beta <- 2

beta_mean <- alpha/(alpha+beta)  # here's the mean of a beta distribution
x <- seq(0, 1, length=100)       # compute dbeta() for these x values
y <- dbeta(x,alpha,beta)
plot(x, y, type="l", las=1, lwd=2, xlab=bquote(theta), ylab="", cex.lab=2)
abline(v=beta_mean)

Likelihood

The likelihood follows the binomial distribution.

\(p(k|N,\theta) = {N\choose k} \theta^k (1-\theta)^{N-k}\)

If we were flipping a coin with bias \(= \theta\), then this distribution tells us the probability of getting any outcome of \(k\) successes from \(N\) flips.

Plot a binomial distribution for all possible \(k\) successes from \(N\) flips, given one particular hypothesis \(\theta\):

N <- 100
theta <- 0.5

k <- seq(0, N, by=1)  # all possible outcomes of k for N flips
y <- dbinom(k,N,theta)
plot(k, y, las=1, lwd=2, xlab="k", ylab="p(k|N,theta)", pch=16)

Note: Ive plotted this as points because k is discrete. \(\theta\) in the other plots can be continuous.

Posterior

The posterior is also a beta distribution.

The posterior tells you what your relative belief in all hypotheses are after observing whatever data you just saw.

Because the Binomial likelihood and Beta prior are conjugate, its very simple to calculate the posterior:

\(Beta(\alpha+s,\beta+f)\)

Where:
\(s =\) the successes (i.e. \(k\)), which in our notation is \(x\)
\(f =\) the failures (i.e. \(N-k\)), which in our notation is \((1-x)\)

Plot the posterior distribution for any prior and any hypothetical data:

k <- 5        # number of observations where the outcome = v1
N <- 10        # total number of observations (must be larger than k)

alpha <- 2    # parameters of prior
beta <- 5

beta_mean <- (alpha+k)/((alpha+k)+(beta+N-k))  # here's the mean of the posterior
x <- seq(0, 1, length=100)                     # compute dbeta() for these values of theta
y <- dbeta(x,alpha+k,beta+N-k)
plot(x, y, type="l", las=1, lwd=2, xlab=bquote(theta), ylab="", cex.lab=2)
abline(v=beta_mean)

Interpretation of posterior: The beta distribution is a probability density function of a continuous random variable. This means the absolute belief in any hypothesis is actually zero - but the relative likelihood of any set of beliefs can be calulated. So if you want to know what your relative belief in \(\theta = (0.5, 0.7,\) or \(0.9)\) is, then compute the ratio of those hypotheses values on the posterior distribution:

thetas <- c(.5,.7,.9)
ys <- dbeta(thetas,alpha+k,beta+N-k)
relative_beliefs <- ys/sum(ys)
print(format(relative_beliefs, scientific=F)) # in case they print in scientific notation
## [1] "0.92945632024" "0.07052749397" "0.00001618579"

Hypothesis choice

Ok now weve computed the posterior. But the agent still needs to choose a hypothesis from the posterior to generate data from.

RG have the agent sample from the posterior (double-check):

# NOT RIGHT YET
#sample(x,prob=(y/sum(y)))

But you could also choose the one on the mean of the distribution. Calculate the beta mean:

beta_mean <- function(alpha,beta,k,N) {
    return((alpha+k)/((alpha+k)+(beta+N-k)))
}
chosen_theta <- beta_mean(alpha,beta,k,N)

Or you could choose the MAP hypothesis (i.e.the one on the mode or peak of the distribution). Calculate the beta mode:

beta_mode <- function(alpha,beta,k,N) {
    if (alpha+k > 1 && beta+N-k > 1) { answer <- (alpha+k-1)/(alpha+k+beta+N-k-2) }
    if (alpha+k == 1 && beta+N-k == 1) { answer <- "all values between 0 and 1 are the mode" }
    if (alpha+k <= 1 && beta+N-k > 1) { answer <- 0 }
    if (alpha+k > 1 && beta+N-k <= 1) { answer <- 1 }
    return(answer)
}
chosen_theta <- beta_mode(alpha,beta,k,N)

Data generation

Data is generated according to the binomial distribution.

Sample \(N\) data points from the binomial distribution for the chosen hypothesis \(\hat\theta\) and count up the number of \(k\) successes you got:

chosen_theta <- 0.5
N <- 10
outcomes <- rbinom(N,size=1,chosen_theta) # size=1 restricts samples to binary digits
k <- sum(outcomes) # 1 = successes, 0 = failures

When this model is iterated to simulate cultural evolution, outcomes is the data that you transmit to the next generation.

Solve the stationary distribution

The stationary distribution is proportional to the first eigenvector of the transition matrix.

Do eigen decomposition on the matrix and grab the first eigenvector:

matrix <- matrix(0,1,1)  # change to TP matrix later

eigvals <- eigen(t(matrix))$values
eigvecs <- eigen(t(matrix))$vectors

stat_dist <- function(matrix) {
    vec <- eigen(t(matrix))$vectors[,1]
    return(vec/sum(vec))
}
